-- Abu Dhabi Shares Gain First Time in 5 Days on Bets Drop Overdone
-- B y   Z a h r a   H a n k i r
-- 2012-01-18T07:29:51Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-01-18/abu-dhabi-shares-gain-first-time-in-5-days-on-bets-drop-overdone.html
Abu Dhabi  shares snapped a four-day
drop amid speculation losses this month prompted by investor
concern that  Dana Gas PJSC (DANA)  would struggle to repay debt were
overdone and as  oil prices  rose for a second day.  Dana Gas headed for the biggest increase in more than two
years after the company, which has a $1 billion Islamic bond
maturing in October, said it will honor its debts.  Sorouh Real
Estate Co. (SOROUH)  rallied 5.8 percent. The  ADX General Index (ADSMI) , down 3.6
percent this month, jumped 1.5 percent, the most since Dec. 29,
to 2,328 at 11:08 a.m. in Abu Dhabi. Dubai’s  DFM General Index (DFMGI) 
advanced 1.2 percent, led by a surge in  Union Properties PJSC. (UPP)   A drop of 1.4 percent the past week has left the  67
companies  in Abu Dhabi’s benchmark gauge valued at an average
7.3 times  estimated earnings , compared with 9.9 times for the
 MSCI Emerging Markets Index. (MXEF)  Abu Dhabi’s measure is valued at
about 1 times net assets, or book value, while emerging markets
stocks are valued at 1.6 times.  “Markets were punished for no significant reason. We
expect a rebound in United Arab Emirates stocks in the coming
few days,” said Tariq Qaqish, deputy head of asset management
at Dubai-based Al Mal Capital. “With international markets on a
better note, and after the announcement of Dana Gas management
that they will honor its sukuk, investor sentiment has
improved.”  About 46  million shares  traded in Abu Dhabi, home to about
7 percent of the world’s proven oil reserves, compared with a
12-month daily average of 63 million shares. Oil for February
delivery rose as much as 0.7 percent to $101.43 a barrel in
electronic trading in  New York  after signs of economic growth in
the U.S. and  Germany  bolstered bets fuel demand may increase.  The  STOXX Europe 600  increased 0.9 percent yesterday and
the  Standard and Poor’s 500 Index  gained 0.4 percent. A report
showed manufacturing in the New York region expanded in January
at the fastest pace in nine months. German investor confidence
rose the most on record in January and Spanish borrowing costs
fell at a debt auction as investors ignored  Standard & Poor’s 
credit-rating downgrades.  Dana Gas advanced 8.8 percent to 37 fils, headed for the
biggest gain since December 2009. “Dana Gas over the last four
years has timely and consistently paid, on or before the due
date, the sukuk profit amount and will continue to do so
pursuant with its obligations,” the company said yesterday.
Sorouh advanced the most since Dec. 29 to 74 fils.  Union Properties soared 15 percent, the most since April
14, to 27.1 fils after  Al Bayan  cited the Dubai developer’s
chairman as saying the company agreed to settle 1.1 billion
dirhams ($299 million) in debt with Emirates NBD PJSC in return
for property assets.  Kuwait’s  measure  rose 0.4 percent and the  Bloomberg GCC 200
Index  gained 0.2 percent. Qatar’s  QE Index (DSM)  declined 0.1 percent,
Oman’s  MSM30 Index (MSM30)  fell 0.1 percent and Bahrain’s  gauge  was
unchanged.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Zahra Hankir in Dubai at 
